This has nothing to do with casting. You just need an `if` statement to check the section.

    if indexPath.section == 0 { // 1 depending on which section you need
        // get the cell and set the background color
    }

But this is going to fail as the user scrolls. What you should be doing in `didSelectRow` is updating your data model to track which rows have been selected and which rows should get a different color background and then telling the table view to reload that row.

Then your code in `cellForRowAt` (or `willDisplay:forRowAt:`) should use that data to set the cell&#39;s colors as needed.

You can override `setSelected(_:animated:)` function in your tableViewCell to update the appearance of your cell when it is selected or unselected. Sample code snippet may be like the one as follows.

```
import UIKit

class CustomTableViewCell: UITableViewCell {

    override func awakeFromNib() {
        super.awakeFromNib()
    }

    override func setSelected(_ selected: Bool, animated: Bool) {
        super.setSelected(selected, animated: animated)

        if selected {
            self.contentView.backgroundColor = .red
        } else {
            self.contentView.backgroundColor = .clear
        }
    }
    
}
```

It will set the background color of the contentView of customcell to red if selected else clear. Hope it helps.

